%FEATURE_STRUCTURES.sofaString:
The patient, a girl, was the first child of healthy non-consanguineous parents. The pregnancy was unremarkable and the prenatal
ultrasound at 20 weeks gestation was normal. Following delivery,
the patient was noted to have deficient skull ossification, bowed
limbs, and omphalocele. The omphalocele was small (33 cm),
contained intestine only, and was closed by primary repair with no
subsequent complications. The head circumference was 35 cm (ca.
50th percentile) but there were widely patent cranial sutures, upslanting palpebral fissures, and a depressed nasal bridge. On examination of the extremities in the neonatal period, the patient was
noted to have bowing of the right lower limb with an associated
anterior skin dimple and leg length discrepancy. The diagnosis of
hypophosphatasia was suspected because of the impaired mineralisation and the radiographic finding of a Bowdler spur of the
right fibula (Fig. 1), generally considered pathognomonic of hypophosphatasia [2, 6,16]. Investigations included a karyotype which
was normal (46,XX) and a skeletal survey which demonstrated
deficient skull ossification and lack of ossification of both clavicles
and pubic rami. Alkaline phosphatase activity at 3 days of age was
22 U/l (reference range for age: 155555 U/l) and all the subsequent measurements of alkaline phosphatase activity have been
below the normal range for age including the most recent value at 9
years of age which was 101 U/l (reference range for age: 185
425 U/l). Urinary phosphoethanolamine was elevated at 46 mmol/
mol creatinine (normal: <10 mmol/mol creatinine) and plasma-5-
pyridoxal phosphate was elevated at 269 nmol/l (normal:
<110 nmol/l). These values are consistent with the diagnosis of
childhood hypophosphatasia.
The patient was re-evaluated at 11.2 years of age. Her psychomotor development was normal. Her general health had been
good but there were two episodes of grand mal seizures secondary
to minor trauma as her skull remained largely unossified (Fig. 2).
Her height was 115 cm (<2nd percentile) and the leg length discrepancy persisted. On examination, her skull had a bilobed appearance due to the cranial vault defect and she had marked
hypertelorism and upslanting palpebral fissures. At age 8 years,
three supernumerary molars which were submerged and ectopically
positioned had been surgically removed. Most of her secondary
teeth were unerupted and those visible were primary dentition. She
was noted have exaggerated lumbar lordosis and mild scoliosis
(Fig. 3a). Review of radiographs revealed findings of classic CCD
including multiple pseudoepiphyses of the metacarpals, hypoplasia
of the clavicles, and hypoplastic pubic rami. The bones were quite
osteopenic in appearance (Fig. 3a, b).
